HEADWORD: Polemarch
<hw>Pol"e*march</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ war
+ <?/ leader, from <?/ to be first.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. Antiq.)</fld>
<def>In Athens, originally, the military commander-in-chief; but,
afterward, a civil magistrate who had jurisdiction in respect of
strangers and sojourners. In other Grecian cities, a high military and
civil officer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

